## **Module 4: Network Security** (Domain 4.0 - 27% of exam)

### **Lesson 21: Network Threats and Vulnerabilities**
**Time:** 30-35 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 4.1, 4.4 - Security concepts and attacks

**Topics Covered:**
- Common network attacks
  - **DoS/DDoS** (Denial of Service)
    - SYN flood
    - UDP flood
    - Ping flood
    - Smurf attack
    - Amplification attacks
  - **On-path attacks** (Man-in-the-middle)
  - **ARP poisoning/spoofing**
  - **MAC flooding**
  - **MAC spoofing**
  - **IP spoofing**
  - **DNS poisoning/spoofing**
  - **VLAN hopping**
  - **Rogue DHCP server**
  - **Evil twin** (wireless)
  - **Deauth attacks** (wireless)
  - **Brute force attacks**
  - **Dictionary attacks**
- Social engineering
  - Phishing
  - Spear phishing
  - Vishing (voice)
  - Smishing (SMS)
  - Tailgating/piggybacking
- Malware types
  - Virus
  - Worm
  - Trojan
  - Ransomware
  - Rootkit
  - Botnet
- Vulnerabilities
  - Unpatched systems
  - Zero-day vulnerabilities
  - Misconfigurations
  - Default credentials
  - Open ports and services
  - Weak passwords
- Security principles
  - Least privilege
  - Defense in depth
  - Zero trust model

---

### **Lesson 22: Authentication Methods**
**Time:** 25-30 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 4.1 - Authentication and authorization

**Topics Covered:**
- Authentication factors
  - Something you know (password, PIN)
  - Something you have (token, smart card)
  - Something you are (biometrics)
- Multi-factor authentication (MFA/2FA)
- Single Sign-On (SSO)
- Authentication protocols
  - **RADIUS** (Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service)
    - Centralized AAA (Authentication, Authorization, Accounting)
    - UDP ports 1812, 1813
    - Common for wireless and VPN
  - **TACACS+** (Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System Plus)
    - Cisco proprietary
    - TCP port 49
    - Separates AAA functions
    - Full packet encryption
  - **Kerberos**
    - Ticket-based authentication
    - KDC (Key Distribution Center)
    - TGT (Ticket Granting Ticket)
    - Mutual authentication
    - Port 88
  - **LDAP/LDAPS** (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol)
    - Directory services (Active Directory)
    - Port 389 (LDAP), 636 (LDAPS)
  - **SAML** (Security Assertion Markup Language)
    - XML-based SSO
  - **OAuth and OpenID Connect**
    - Delegated authorization
- Local authentication vs centralized
- 802.1X (port-based network access control)
  - Supplicant, authenticator, authentication server
  - EAP (Extensible Authentication Protocol)

---

### **Lesson 23: VPNs and Remote Access**
**Time:** 30-35 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 4.4 - Remote access methods

**Topics Covered:**
- VPN (Virtual Private Network) concepts
  - Purpose: secure remote access and site-to-site connectivity
  - Encryption and tunneling
- VPN types
  - **Site-to-site VPN**
    - Connects two networks
    - Always-on
    - Router-to-router
  - **Remote access VPN (client-to-site)**
    - Individual users connecting remotely
    - On-demand or always-on
- VPN protocols
  - **IPSec (Internet Protocol Security)**
    - Suite of protocols
    - AH (Authentication Header)
    - ESP (Encapsulating Security Payload)
    - IKE (Internet Key Exchange)
    - Transport mode vs tunnel mode
  - **SSL/TLS VPN**
    - Browser-based or client-based
    - Port 443 (looks like HTTPS)
    - Easier to deploy (no client needed for clientless)
  - **PPTP** (Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol) - legacy, insecure
  - **L2TP** (Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol)
    - Usually combined with IPSec (L2TP/IPSec)
  - **OpenVPN**
    - Open source
    - SSL/TLS-based
  - **WireGuard**
    - Modern, lightweight
    - Fast performance
- VPN concentrators
- Split tunneling vs full tunneling
- Remote desktop protocols
  - **RDP** (Remote Desktop Protocol) - port 3389
  - **VNC** (Virtual Network Computing)
  - **SSH** (Secure Shell) - port 22
- Remote access security
  - VPN authentication
  - VPN encryption (AES)
  - Certificate-based authentication

---

### **Lesson 24: Firewalls and Access Control Lists**
**Time:** 30-35 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 4.1, 4.3 - Firewalls and ACLs

**Topics Covered:**
- Firewall fundamentals
  - Purpose: filter traffic based on rules
  - Inbound vs outbound rules
  - Implicit deny (default deny all)
- Firewall types
  - **Stateless firewall (packet filtering)**
    - Examines each packet independently
    - Checks against ACL rules
    - Fast but limited
  - **Stateful firewall**
    - Tracks connection state
    - Allows return traffic for established connections
    - More secure
  - **Next-Generation Firewall (NGFW)**
    - Application awareness
    - Deep packet inspection (DPI)
    - Integrated IPS
    - User/identity awareness
    - SSL inspection
  - **Web Application Firewall (WAF)**
    - Protects web applications
    - Layer 7 filtering
- Firewall deployment
  - Network-based firewalls
  - Host-based firewalls (software)
  - Screened subnet (DMZ)
- Access Control Lists (ACLs)
  - Standard ACLs (source IP only)
  - Extended ACLs (source, destination, protocol, port)
  - ACL placement (as close to source as possible)
  - Wildcard masks
  - Permit and deny statements
  - ACL processing (top to bottom)
  - Implicit deny at end
- DMZ (Demilitarized Zone)
  - Screened subnet
  - Public-facing servers (web, email, DNS)
  - Two firewalls (front and back)
- NAT (Network Address Translation) on firewalls
  - Static NAT (one-to-one)
  - Dynamic NAT (pool)
  - PAT/NAT overload (many-to-one)
- Port forwarding

---

### **Lesson 25: Network Segmentation and Zero Trust**
**Time:** 25-30 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 4.1, 4.3 - Segmentation and security

**Topics Covered:**
- Network segmentation concepts
  - Dividing networks into smaller segments
  - Benefits: security, performance, compliance
- Segmentation methods
  - VLANs (logical segmentation)
  - Subnets (IP-based segmentation)
  - Physical segmentation
- Screened subnets (DMZ)
  - Placing public servers in isolated network
  - Dual firewall architecture
- Internal segmentation
  - Separating departments
  - Guest networks
  - IoT network isolation
  - Management network (out-of-band)
- Microsegmentation
  - Application-level segmentation
  - East-west traffic filtering
- Zero Trust security model
  - "Never trust, always verify"
  - Principles:
    - Verify explicitly
    - Least privilege access
    - Assume breach
  - Implementation:
    - Continuous authentication
    - Device compliance checks
    - Microsegmentation
    - Encryption everywhere
- Network Access Control (NAC)
  - 802.1X authentication
  - Posture assessment
  - Quarantine VLANs
  - Guest access
- Security zones
  - Trusted zone (internal network)
  - Untrusted zone (internet)
  - DMZ (semi-trusted)

---

### **Lesson 26: Wireless Security (WPA3, EAP)**
**Time:** 25-30 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 4.4 - Wireless security

**Topics Covered:**
- Wireless security protocols
  - **WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy)**
    - Deprecated, insecure (crackable in minutes)
    - 64-bit or 128-bit keys
    - Never use
  - **WPA (Wi-Fi Protected Access)**
    - TKIP encryption
    - Better than WEP but still vulnerable
    - Deprecated
  - **WPA2 (802.11i)**
    - AES encryption (CCMP)
    - Personal (PSK - Pre-Shared Key)
    - Enterprise (802.1X authentication)
    - Industry standard until WPA3
  - **WPA3**
    - Latest standard (2018)
    - SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals)
    - Forward secrecy
    - Protection against offline dictionary attacks
    - Enhanced Open (for public networks)
    - 192-bit encryption in Enterprise mode
- WPA2/WPA3 modes
  - **Personal (PSK)**
    - Single password for all users
    - Home networks, small offices
  - **Enterprise (802.1X)**
    - Individual user credentials
    - RADIUS authentication
    - Certificate-based or username/password
- EAP (Extensible Authentication Protocol) methods
  - **EAP-TLS** (Transport Layer Security)
    - Certificate-based (most secure)
    - Requires PKI
    - Mutual authentication
  - **EAP-TTLS** (Tunneled TLS)
    - Server-side certificate only
    - Tunnel for other auth methods
  - **PEAP** (Protected EAP)
    - Similar to EAP-TTLS
    - MSCHAPv2 commonly used inside tunnel
  - **EAP-FAST** (Flexible Authentication via Secure Tunneling)
    - Cisco proprietary
    - PAC (Protected Access Credential)
- Wireless security best practices
  - Strong encryption (WPA2/WPA3)
  - Disable WPS (Wi-Fi Protected Setup)
  - Change default SSID
  - Disable SSID broadcast (security through obscurity - limited benefit)
  - MAC filtering (limited security, can be spoofed)
  - Strong Wi-Fi passwords (minimum 12+ characters)
  - Guest network isolation
  - Regular firmware updates
- Wireless authentication methods
  - Open (no authentication)
  - PSK (Pre-Shared Key)
  - 802.1X (Enterprise)
  - Captive portal

---

## **Module 5: Network Troubleshooting** (Domain 5.0 - 22% of exam)

### **Lesson 27: Troubleshooting Methodology**
**Time:** 20-25 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 5.1 - Network troubleshooting methodology

**Topics Covered:**
- CompTIA troubleshooting methodology (7 steps)
  1. **Identify the problem**
     - Gather information
     - Question users
     - Identify symptoms
     - Determine recent changes
     - Duplicate the problem if possible
  2. **Establish a theory of probable cause**
     - Question the obvious
     - Consider multiple approaches (OSI model)
     - Top-to-bottom vs bottom-to-top
  3. **Test the theory to determine the cause**
     - If theory confirmed, move to next step
     - If theory not confirmed, establish new theory
  4. **Establish a plan of action**
     - Determine steps to resolve
     - Consider impact on users/business
  5. **Implement the solution or escalate**
     - Make one change at a time
     - Document changes
     - Escalate if beyond scope
  6. **Verify full system functionality**
     - Test solution
     - Verify with user
     - Implement preventive measures if possible
  7. **Document findings, actions, and outcomes**
     - Update documentation
     - Lessons learned
     - Knowledge base articles
- Troubleshooting best practices
  - Always check the simple things first
  - Don't assume
  - Use the OSI model
  - Establish baselines
  - Consider recent changes
  - Have backups and rollback plan

---

### **Lesson 28: Command-Line Tools**
**Time:** 30-35 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 5.3 - Network troubleshooting tools

**Topics Covered:**
- Essential command-line tools
  - **ping**
    - Tests connectivity (ICMP echo request/reply)
    - Verifies IP connectivity
    - Shows latency (round-trip time)
    - Usage: `ping 8.8.8.8` or `ping google.com`
    - Options: -t (continuous), -n (count), -l (packet size)
  - **tracert / traceroute**
    - Shows path packets take (all hops)
    - Identifies where connectivity fails
    - Uses ICMP (Windows) or UDP (Linux/Mac)
    - TTL incrementation
    - Usage: `tracert google.com`
  - **ipconfig / ifconfig / ip**
    - Displays IP configuration
    - `ipconfig` (Windows)
    - `ifconfig` (Mac/Linux - deprecated)
    - `ip addr` (Linux - modern)
    - `ipconfig /all` - detailed info
    - `ipconfig /release` - release DHCP
    - `ipconfig /renew` - renew DHCP
    - `ipconfig /flushdns` - clear DNS cache
  - **nslookup / dig**
    - DNS lookup tools
    - Queries DNS records
    - `nslookup google.com`
    - `nslookup google.com 8.8.8.8` (query specific DNS server)
    - `dig google.com` (more detailed, Linux/Mac)
  - **netstat**
    - Network statistics
    - Shows active connections
    - `netstat -a` (all connections and listening ports)
    - `netstat -n` (numerical addresses)
    - `netstat -r` (routing table)
    - `netstat -ano` (with PIDs)
  - **arp**
    - ARP table (IP to MAC address mappings)
    - `arp -a` (view ARP cache)
    - `arp -d` (clear ARP cache)
  - **route**
    - View and modify routing table
    - `route print` (Windows)
    - `route add` (add static route)
    - `route delete` (remove route)
  - **hostname**
    - Displays computer's hostname
  - **nbtstat** (Windows)
    - NetBIOS over TCP/IP statistics
    - `nbtstat -a` (remote machine's NetBIOS names)
    - `nbtstat -n` (local NetBIOS names)
  - **pathping** (Windows)
    - Combines ping and tracert
    - Shows packet loss per hop
  - **mtr** (Linux/Mac)
    - Continuous traceroute with statistics
- Advanced tools
  - **tcpdump / Wireshark**
    - Packet capture and analysis
    - Deep packet inspection
  - **curl / wget**
    - HTTP requests from command line
  - **ssh**
    - Secure remote shell access
  - **telnet**
    - Test port connectivity
    - `telnet google.com 80`

---

### **Lesson 29: Cable Testing and Physical Layer Issues**
**Time:** 25-30 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 5.2, 5.3 - Hardware tools and physical issues

**Topics Covered:**
- Physical layer problems
  - Bad cables
  - Incorrect cable type
  - Wrong pinout (T568A vs T568B mismatch)
  - Cable distance too long
  - Interference (EMI/RFI)
  - Damaged connectors
  - Bad ports/transceivers
- Cable testing tools
  - **Cable tester**
    - Tests continuity
    - Wire mapping
    - Identifies opens, shorts, miswires
  - **Tone generator and probe (toner)**
    - Traces cables
    - Identifies which cable is which
  - **Loopback adapter**
    - Tests network interface
    - Physical and virtual loopbacks
  - **TDR (Time Domain Reflectometer)**
    - Measures cable length
    - Locates breaks in copper cables
  - **OTDR (Optical TDR)**
    - Tests fiber optic cables
    - Measures attenuation
    - Locates breaks/bends
  - **Light meter (optical power meter)**
    - Tests fiber signal strength
  - **Multimeter**
    - Tests voltage, continuity, resistance
  - **Cable certifier**
    - Certifies cable meets standards (Cat5e, Cat6, etc.)
    - Tests performance at rated speeds
  - **Spectrum analyzer**
    - Analyzes wireless frequencies
    - Identifies interference
  - **Wi-Fi analyzer**
    - Shows nearby wireless networks
    - Channel usage
    - Signal strength
- Common cable issues
  - **Attenuation** - signal loss over distance
  - **Crosstalk** - interference between wire pairs
    - NEXT (Near-End Crosstalk)
    - FEXT (Far-End Crosstalk)
  - **EMI/RFI** - electromagnetic/radio frequency interference
  - **Incorrect termination**
  - **Bent/broken cables**
  - **Dirty/scratched fiber connectors**
- Link lights and LEDs
  - Solid green = good link
  - Blinking = activity
  - Amber/orange = issues (speed mismatch, etc.)
  - No light = no connection

---

### **Lesson 30: Common Network Issues and Solutions**
**Time:** 30-35 minutes  
**Exam Objectives:** 5.2, 5.4, 5.5 - Common issues and troubleshooting

**Topics Covered:**
- Connectivity issues
  - **No connectivity**
    - Check Layer 1 (cables, lights)
    - Check IP configuration
    - Check default gateway
    - Ping gateway, ping internet
  - **Intermittent connectivity**
    - Loose cables
    - Interference (wireless)
    - Failing hardware
    - High utilization/congestion
  - **Limited connectivity (APIPA 169.254.x.x)**
    - DHCP server down or unreachable
    - No more DHCP addresses available
    - DHCP not configured
  - **Can ping IP but not hostname**
    - DNS issue
    - Check DNS server configuration
    - Flush DNS cache
  - **Can reach local network but not internet**
    - Default gateway issue
    - DNS issue
    - Router/firewall problem
  - **Slow network performance**
    - Bandwidth saturation
    - Duplex mismatch (half/full)
    - Latency/jitter issues
    - QoS misconfiguration
- IP addressing issues
  - **DHCP issues**
    - DHCP scope exhausted
    - Rogue DHCP server
    - DHCP relay not configured
  - **IP address conflicts**
    - Duplicate static IPs
    - Short DHCP lease times
  - **Incorrect subnet mask**
    - Can't reach certain hosts
  - **Incorrect gateway**
    - Can't reach outside local network
- Name resolution issues
  - **DNS problems**
    - Cannot resolve names
    - Incorrect DNS server
    - DNS cache poisoning
- Wireless issues
  - **Poor signal strength/coverage**
    - Insufficient APs
    - Interference
    - Channel overlap
    - Physical obstructions
  - **Channel overlap/interference**
    - Use non-overlapping channels (1, 6, 11)
    - Switch to 5 GHz
  - **Incorrect SSID/password**
  - **Security type mismatch**
  - **Insufficient wireless bandwidth**
  - **Rogue access point**
- Switching/VLAN issues
  - **VLAN mismatch**
    - Access port on wrong VLAN
    - Native VLAN mismatch on trunk
  - **Spanning tree issues**
    - Root bridge election problems
    - Topology changes causing reconvergence
    - Port blocking when shouldn't
  - **Broadcast storms**
    - Layer 2 loops
    - STP disabled or misconfigured
- Routing issues
  - **Missing routes**
    - Static route not configured
    - Routing protocol not advertising
  - **Routing loops**
    - Split horizon disabled
    - Improper summarization
  - **Asymmetric routing**
- Performance issues
  - **High latency**
    - Long distance
    - Congestion
    - Routing inefficiency
  - **Jitter** (variable latency)
    - Congestion
    - Affects VoIP/video
  - **Packet loss**
    - Congestion
    - Faulty cables/hardware
    - Errors on interface
  - **Throughput issues**
    - Bandwidth saturation
    - Duplex mismatch
    - QoS misconfiguration
- Hardware issues
  - **Port flapping** (up/down/up/down)
    - Bad cable
    - Faulty port/transceiver
    - Auto-negotiation issues
  - **CRC errors** (Cyclic Redundancy Check)
    - Bad cable
    - EMI/interference
    - Duplex mismatch
  - **Collisions** (should be 0 on switched networks)
    - Duplex mismatch
    - Hub still in use
  - **Giants/Runts**
    - Oversized/undersized frames
    - Usually indicates hardware problem

